- Generate SonarQube Token and Configure Webhook in Jenkins
------------------------------------------------------------
step 1: Generate SonarQube Token
Log in to SonarQube.
Go to:
Administration → Security → Users → (Select your user) → Tokens
Click Generate Token.
Give it a name (e.g., jenkins-token) and copy the token.
Important: Copy it now, you won’t see it again.

Step 2: Add SonarQube Token in Jenkins
Log in to Jenkins.
Go to:
Manage Jenkins → Credentials → (Global) → Add Credentials
Choose Kind → Secret text.
Paste the SonarQube token.
Give it an ID (e.g., sonarqube-token) → Save.

Step 3: Configure SonarQube Endpoint in Jenkins
Go to:
Manage Jenkins → Configure System → SonarQube
Click Add SonarQube.
Fill in:
Name: sonar-server
Server URL (SonarQube endpoint): http://65.2.184.54:9000
Server authentication token: Select the secret you just added (sonarqube-token)
Save the configuration.

Step 4: Configure Webhook in SonarQube
In SonarQube, go to:
Administration → Configuration → Webhooks → Create
Fill in:
Name: jenkins-sonar-webhook
URL: http://<jenkins-server>:8080/sonarqube-webhook (e.g., http://65.2.137.252:8080/sonarqube-webhook)
Save the webhook.

 - Docker credentials
-------------------
Click (global) → Add Credentials.
Choose Kind depending on your setup:
Username with password
Enter your DockerHub / registry username and password / token.
Give it a meaningful ID (e.g., dockerhub-credentials).
Secret text
If your Docker registry uses an access token.
SSH Username with private key
If you’re authenticating to a private registry with SSH.
Click Save.

- Snyk Account Token
-----------------------
https://app.snyk.io/account
1.Add Snyk token to Jenkins Credentials
Go to Jenkins → Manage Jenkins → Credentials → Global → Add Credentials.

Select:
Kind: Secret text
Secret: <your Snyk token>
ID: Snyk-Token 




